{
  "text": "Many organizational strategies are based on the timing of each task, as getting the timing of certain activities right can determine the future of firms, and even their remaining in the market or their failure (Bird & West, 1998) . In general, in the early years of a business, entrepreneurs make decisions to exploit the opportunities being offered by the market and maximize the chances of the enterprise's performing better in the future [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . This varies according to the life history of the entrepreneurs [CITATION_3] . Such opportunities can arise out of weaknesses seen in competitors or customer desires which are not fully satisfied, thereby making these actors (competitors and customers) impact on decisions that could lead to a firm's good performance [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "154987602",
    "[CITATION_2]": "153880775",
